# Terms
Protocol:
Throughput: The actual data transfer rate observed in a network
# Network: A collection of interconnected devices that can communicate with each other
# Node: Any device connected to a network (e.g., computer, printer, router)
# Bandwidth: The maximum rate of data transfer across a network path
Topology: The arrangement of devices in a network (e.g., star, mesh, bus, ring)

Network Models:
- OSI Model
- TCP/IP Model

Routing Protocols: Learn about protocols such as RIP, OSPF, and BGP that determine the best path for data
Switching Concepts: Understand how switches operate to forward data within a LAN

# Network Devices:
# - Modem: Modulator & Demodulator, Converts digital signals to analog and vice versa
# - Access Point: Works like a Wi-Fi extender but also creates a new Wi-Fi network to connect wireless devices to a wired network
# - Hub: Dumb, because it sends data to all devices without any traffic management
# - Switch: Smart, as it uses MAC addr to send data only to the intended device, managing traffic efficiently
